dom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Upton, Norfolk, England":"Upton, Norfolk, England","Witchingham, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Blofield, Norfolk, England":"Blofield, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1308–1360":"1308–1360","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1328–1381":"1328–1381","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1338":"circa 1338","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Witchingham, St Faith's, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Upton, Norfolk, England":"Upton, Norfolk, England","Witchingham, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Blofield, Norfolk, England":"Blofield, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1308–1360":"1308–1360","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1328–1381":"1328–1381","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1338":"about 1338","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Witchingham, St Faith's, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Upton, Norfolk, England":"Upton, Norfolk, England","Witchingham, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Blofield, Norfolk, England":"Blofield, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":20,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":29,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Roger Wychingham was born in 1308, in Blofield, Norfolk, England. He married Margaret Antingham in 1327, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1360, in Upton, Norfolk, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1308–1360":"1308–1360","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1328–1381":"1328–1381","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1338":"umbes 1338","1327":"1327","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Witchingham, St Faith's, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upton, Norfolk, England":"Upton, Norfolk, England","Witchingham, Norfolk, England":"Witchingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blofield, Norfolk